Advertise your product or brand here
contact www.OpenSubtitles.org today

00:45.745 --> 00:46.957
(HORN HONKS)

01:01.394 --> 01:02.527
(SIGHS)

01:22.866 --> 01:24.106
(PAPER SHUFFLING)

01:29.347 --> 01:30.809
(HORN HONKS)

01:32.571 --> 01:33.762
♪ ♪

01:41.059 --> 01:42.395
JACK: Hey, guys?

01:42.420 --> 01:45.614
- Slow down. Watch out. The...
- I want a pink car!

01:45.655 --> 01:47.161
- Sorry. Sorry about that.
- No, we have to get a Porsche!

01:47.319 --> 01:48.951
- It's got to be the same car as...
- Shh.

01:48.975 --> 01:50.534
[ALL CHATTERING EXCITEDLY]

01:50.535 --> 01:52.035
- Guys.
- Hey. Shh. Come here.

01:52.060 --> 01:55.004
Can I remind you that we are
guests in this dealership?

01:55.029 --> 01:57.661
Yes. So we're gonna use
our indoor voices.

01:58.270 --> 02:00.436
Okay, look, go sit down over
there and enjoy the free A.C.

02:00.505 --> 02:02.684
- Mom and Dad need to negotiate.
- (SIGHS)

02:02.934 --> 02:05.642
- I should've gotten a sitter.
- No. No, not today.

02:05.710 --> 02:07.675
Look, they are walking embodiments

02:07.700 --> 02:09.933
of why we're so strapped for cash, Bec.

02:10.536 --> 02:12.721
Do you mean to tell me
you're gonna use our children

02:12.746 --> 02:14.503
to guilt them into
giving us a good deal?

02:14.528 --> 02:16.300
Yeah. That's exactly what I'm gonna do.

02:16.325 --> 02:17.481
- (LAUGHS)
- Mm-hmm.

02:17.506 --> 02:19.356
You are so bad.

02:19.381 --> 02:21.262
- Am I?
- (WHISPERS): You're so bad.

02:21.747 --> 02:22.926
MEL: I love it!

02:23.552 --> 02:27.320
You two are just the sort of
bright and shiny couple

02:27.389 --> 02:30.890
I would love to put into this
bright and shiny Jeep Wagoneer.

02:30.959 --> 02:32.356
- Hi. Mel Buchanan.
- JACK: Hey.

02:32.381 --> 02:34.059
Jack Pearson. This is my wife Rebecca.

02:34.084 --> 02:35.114
- Hi.
- Hi.

02:35.139 --> 02:38.017
No, I think the, uh, Wagoneer's
a little too steep for us.

02:38.042 --> 02:39.075
REBECCA: Mm-hmm.

02:39.100 --> 02:41.114
Well, luckily for you,
I'm in a good mood. (LAUGHS)

02:41.552 --> 02:43.589
In fact, I'm in a downright stupid mood.

02:43.614 --> 02:45.918
- I'm gonna practically...
- Mel. I'm gonna stop you

02:45.943 --> 02:47.746
right there. Do you see
those kids over there?

02:47.927 --> 02:49.692
- JACK: They're ours.
- REBECCA: All of them.

02:49.739 --> 02:52.184
- They're expensive. (CHUCKLES)
- All of them.

02:52.660 --> 02:54.903
We don't really need
anything bright and shiny.

02:54.933 --> 02:57.543
We just want something
reliable and affordable.

02:57.569 --> 02:58.911
- Yeah.
- And safe.

03:00.872 --> 03:04.223
Well, uh, we've got some
used cars, right this way.

03:04.426 --> 03:05.809
- There we go.
- All right.

03:06.801 --> 03:10.645
I mean, it's not flashy,
but, uh, it's got low mileage.

03:10.691 --> 03:12.324
Big trunk. Um...

03:12.907 --> 03:15.675
It's gonna have
a few good years left in her.

03:15.744 --> 03:18.067
Everything is automatic on the inside...

03:19.447 --> 03:21.120
(KIDS CHATTERING EXCITEDLY)

03:21.145 --> 03:22.191
- Whoo!

03:22.216 --> 03:24.082
- Oh, my gosh!
- REBECCA: I mean, I think it...

03:24.107 --> 03:26.442
...it warrants a closer look.
What do you think, babe?

03:28.286 --> 03:30.748
I think, Mel, you and I should
go into your office

03:30.817 --> 03:33.450
and have a talk, see if we can't
figure something out.

03:33.475 --> 03:36.276
But, Jack, we should at least
look at the car, though, first,

03:36.327 --> 03:37.827
before you go in there and talk to him.

03:37.852 --> 03:39.785
We haven't even looked at the car yet.

03:50.308 --> 03:51.653
How's your leg feeling?

03:52.356 --> 03:53.520
Good as new.

03:54.551 --> 03:55.706
REBECCA: Guys.

03:55.775 --> 03:58.509
Could you hurry up, please? Come on.

03:58.578 --> 04:00.729
- The service doesn't start until 2:00.
- Yeah.

04:00.754 --> 04:02.847
But I want to get there
now, so let's go.

04:03.087 --> 04:04.231
♪ ♪

04:19.647 --> 04:20.831
How'd it go?

04:20.856 --> 04:22.176
- Pretty good.
- Yeah?

04:22.201 --> 04:23.340
Yeah.

04:24.717 --> 04:25.981
I got the Wagoneer.

04:26.847 --> 04:27.900
What?

04:28.129 --> 04:29.399
Jack. No, no, no.

04:29.424 --> 04:31.325
- We can't afford that car.
- We can.

04:31.496 --> 04:33.004
He gave us a pretty good deal.

04:33.082 --> 04:35.942
It's just a little bit more
than what we wanted to spend,

04:35.967 --> 04:37.356
but we're okay.

04:37.657 --> 04:39.286
Well, what did you say to him?

04:40.457 --> 04:41.567
Ah...

04:43.457 --> 04:44.825
(BOTH LAUGH)

04:45.715 --> 04:47.715
Tell the kids. I'm-I'm gonna
go finish up with him.

04:47.740 --> 04:49.254
- Okay.
- All right.

04:51.680 --> 04:52.871
Uh, you guys?

04:54.168 --> 04:56.443
Your dad bought the Wagoneer.

04:56.468 --> 04:58.234
- (KIDS CHEERING)
- (REBECCA LAUGHING)

05:01.857 --> 05:03.161
♪ ♪

05:34.332 --> 05:39.698
synced and corrected by susinz
*www.addic7ed.com*

05:43.501 --> 05:45.831
REBECCA: Hey. Who's excited
about going to see

05:45.856 --> 05:46.990
their first concert?

05:47.015 --> 05:48.426
-KIDS: Me!
-REBECCA: Yeah?

05:48.451 --> 05:49.698
Could we get Weird Al's
autograph after?

05:49.723 --> 05:52.291
Yeah, maybe. I mean,
crazier things have happened.

05:52.598 --> 05:53.933
(MUSIC PLAYING OVER RADIO)

05:54.674 --> 05:57.329
- Bec, coming up on that bridge.
- (REBECCA GROANS)

05:57.471 --> 05:59.983
The bridge Mom always
closes her eyes for?

06:00.008 --> 06:02.325
-Yep.
-Mm. I hate this crumbling old thing.

06:02.350 --> 06:03.385
All right, look here, come here.

06:03.410 --> 06:05.007
Give me your hand. We'll just
do our thing, all right?

06:05.032 --> 06:07.104
Just squeeze my hand,
keep your eyes closed.

06:07.129 --> 06:09.226
-We'll be over it real soon, okay?
-Okay.

06:09.251 --> 06:10.869
JACK:
Okay. Here we go.

06:11.953 --> 06:13.850
Uh-oh.

06:14.207 --> 06:15.598
"Uh-oh"? What does "uh-oh" mean?

06:15.805 --> 06:18.499
- Why are we stopping?
- There's some construction up ahead.

06:18.524 --> 06:19.594
They've got it narrowed down

06:19.619 --> 06:20.825
-to just one lane right now.
-What?

06:20.850 --> 06:22.676
-Babe.
-No, no, no, no, no.

06:22.701 --> 06:24.735
Please don't tell me
that I'm gonna die on my way

06:24.760 --> 06:26.307
to a "Weird Al" Yankovic
concert.

06:26.332 --> 06:28.785
-I thought you said you like him.
-She does, Kev.

06:29.605 --> 06:31.829
You know, Bec, this is probably gonna
take a minute. You may want to just

06:31.854 --> 06:33.243
- open your eyes this time.
- No.

06:33.268 --> 06:34.835
Babe, I can't. You know I can't.

06:34.860 --> 06:36.618
I know it's totally irrational,
but...

06:37.089 --> 06:39.057
-I can't open my eyes.
-Okay. All right.

06:39.186 --> 06:40.413
KATE:
Is Mom okay?

06:40.438 --> 06:42.906
-Yeah. Yeah, Mom is fine, Kate.
-(REBECCA GROANS)

06:42.931 --> 06:45.031
You know what, how about we all
give Mom just a little bit

06:45.056 --> 06:47.454
of quiet right now,
just a little bit of quiet.

06:47.479 --> 06:48.740
Okay?

06:50.801 --> 06:52.033
(EXHALES)

06:52.097 --> 06:54.036
Do you know what fear of bridges
is called, Mom?

06:54.061 --> 06:55.877
Hey, know what, that's-that's
the opposite of quiet, bud.

06:55.902 --> 06:57.536
No, it's okay. It's okay.

06:57.889 --> 07:00.171
What's it called, babe?
Go ahead, distract me.

07:00.206 --> 07:01.566
Gephyrophobia.

07:02.329 --> 07:04.165
-Gephyrophobia.
-I've memorized all the phobias.

07:04.292 --> 07:05.855
-Huh.
-What? You have?

07:06.142 --> 07:07.575
That is very impressive.

07:07.880 --> 07:09.108
-Thank you.
-Um...

07:09.133 --> 07:11.465
Okay, guys, who's next?
Tell me something else.

07:11.490 --> 07:13.791
Um, you want to hear
my favorite "Weird Al" song?

07:13.816 --> 07:15.564
-Yes, I do. Go for it.
-JACK: (LAUGHS) There we go.

07:15.663 --> 07:17.631
♪ <i>La-la-la-la-lasagna</i> ♪

07:17.656 --> 07:19.489
♪ <i>You want some lasagna</i> ♪

07:19.514 --> 07:21.214
KIDS:
♪ <i>Magnifico</i> ♪

07:21.239 --> 07:23.081
♪ <i>Or maybe spaghetti</i> ♪

07:23.106 --> 07:24.973
-(LAUGHS): You're gonna sing too?
-♪ <i>Your supper is ready</i> ♪

07:24.998 --> 07:26.511
♪ <i>Now where you go?</i> ♪

07:26.536 --> 07:29.837
-♪ <i>Mama mia bambino</i> ♪
-Hey! Hey, we're moving.

07:30.123 --> 07:31.261
REBECCA:
We're moving!

07:31.286 --> 07:32.531
Keep singing! Keep singing!

07:32.556 --> 07:33.864
♪ <i>Mama mia bambino</i> ♪

07:33.889 --> 07:36.459
♪ <i>La-lasagna</i> ♪

07:36.484 --> 07:38.318
-♪ <i>La-lasagna</i> ♪
-Almost there.

07:38.343 --> 07:39.868
(KIDS CONTINUE SINGING)

07:40.598 --> 07:43.066
-JACK: We're off the bridge.
-(SHRIEKS) It worked!

08:00.193 --> 08:02.138
Did we really have to
rush out the door like that?

08:02.163 --> 08:03.592
You know, I'm not even
done getting dressed.

08:03.617 --> 08:07.162
REBECCA: Yes. We have to be to the
cemetery before the urn gets there.

08:07.225 --> 08:09.615
Why do we have to get there
before the urn gets there?

08:09.640 --> 08:10.998
Because we just do.

08:12.849 --> 08:15.240
I forgot to put Louie
in his crate before we left.

08:16.729 --> 08:18.271
He's gonna pee on the carpet.

08:19.234 --> 08:21.716
Okay, then he pees
all over the carpet, Kate.

08:27.130 --> 08:28.865
I don't want him anymore, anyway.

08:30.099 --> 08:33.154
I'm gonna ask around and see
if anyone wants to take a dog.

08:34.458 --> 08:35.466
Okay.

08:37.076 --> 08:38.821
That's fine. Go ahead and ask around.

08:39.287 --> 08:40.498
Damn it.

08:41.907 --> 08:43.748
You have to make the fat part longer.

08:48.615 --> 08:50.435
I can help you with it
if you want me to.

08:50.513 --> 08:53.552
No, screw it. I'm not wearing a tie.

08:53.648 --> 08:55.948
You're not gonna wear a
tie to Dad's funeral?

08:56.028 --> 08:57.295
He wouldn't care.

09:06.256 --> 09:08.130
JACK: Ah, looks like it started snowing.

09:08.218 --> 09:09.714
Watch your step, babe. It's ahh...

09:10.154 --> 09:11.490
It could be slippery.

09:11.528 --> 09:12.568
Thank you.

09:14.269 --> 09:15.615
(EXHALES, SHIVERS)

09:19.002 --> 09:20.670
- (EXHALES)
- Yeah.

09:24.248 --> 09:25.302
Hey.

09:27.865 --> 09:30.722
The doctors, they're-they're
just being cautious.

09:31.670 --> 09:34.082
In a few hours,
they'll call us with the results

09:34.084 --> 09:36.862
of the MRI, and they're gonna
tell us that you are fine.

09:37.349 --> 09:40.887
(SIGHS) Babe, I've just been
so dizzy all week.

09:40.912 --> 09:43.291
- I've never felt like this before.
- I know. I know.

09:43.293 --> 09:45.349
And it's probably
just an inner ear thing.

09:46.052 --> 09:47.240
All right?

09:47.357 --> 09:50.216
They just... they just got to be sure

09:50.241 --> 09:51.927
that it's not something really serious.

09:52.115 --> 09:53.263
- That's all.
- Yeah.

09:53.288 --> 09:55.576
- Like a brain tumor.
- Right.

09:57.591 --> 09:58.723
All right, let's just...

09:58.748 --> 10:01.459
let's go back to the house
and wait for them to call.

10:03.779 --> 10:05.521
I'm gonna go crazy
if we're waiting at the house.

10:05.523 --> 10:06.826
Let's, um...

10:08.160 --> 10:10.037
You know what,
they've got my pager number.

10:10.716 --> 10:12.404
I want to take you someplace special.

10:12.686 --> 10:13.880
(ENGINE STARTS)

10:20.053 --> 10:21.232
So, here it is.

10:22.332 --> 10:23.513
My favorite tree.

10:24.505 --> 10:26.834
I had no idea you had a favorite tree.

10:27.220 --> 10:28.935
I'm full of surprises.

10:31.548 --> 10:32.685
(JACK SIGHS)

10:34.772 --> 10:36.747
How are you right now? Dizzy?

10:37.437 --> 10:38.662
No, I'm okay.

10:39.085 --> 10:40.670
Sort of comes and goes.

10:41.209 --> 10:42.341
Okay.

10:48.474 --> 10:49.447
All right?

10:49.472 --> 10:52.184
Sorry. I'm being such a baby
about all of this.

10:52.209 --> 10:53.341
Hey, listen to me.

10:53.685 --> 10:56.588
Rebecca, you are gonna live forever.

10:57.779 --> 11:01.060
- (SCOFFS) Okay, Jack.
- No. Hey, Bec, listen.

11:01.924 --> 11:02.982
You are.

11:04.232 --> 11:06.431
Look, I know in my bones
today is not the day

11:06.433 --> 11:08.266
the world gives us bad news.

11:09.138 --> 11:10.295
Okay?

11:10.570 --> 11:11.724
Today...

11:13.396 --> 11:16.912
this beautiful, perfect day...

11:18.209 --> 11:21.709
is the day that
my beautiful, perfect wife

11:22.813 --> 11:24.154
finds out she's okay.

11:28.806 --> 11:31.128
How are you always so sure
about these things?

11:34.620 --> 11:37.529
How is the snow still gonna fall
if you're not around to see it?

11:39.202 --> 11:40.698
Just wouldn't seem right.

11:44.465 --> 11:45.823
(JACK BREATHES DEEPLY)

11:50.472 --> 11:52.964
REBECCA: Why is this your favorite tree?

11:54.236 --> 11:57.237
Because this is where
you find out you're okay.

12:01.035 --> 12:02.261
(PAGER RINGING)

12:11.988 --> 12:13.409
There's a phone. Let's go.

12:13.909 --> 12:14.979
Okay.

12:16.339 --> 12:18.015
Hi, this is Rebecca Pearson.

12:18.017 --> 12:19.984
Um, somebody just paged my husband.

12:19.986 --> 12:22.206
I think the results of my MRI are in.

12:27.237 --> 12:28.292
(EXHALES)

12:28.823 --> 12:30.227
That's great news.

12:31.050 --> 12:32.519
So it is just the ear thing?

12:32.776 --> 12:34.019
You're sure?

12:35.498 --> 12:37.034
Wow. Thank you so much.

12:37.979 --> 12:39.511
Yeah. Okay, thank you.

12:40.167 --> 12:41.347
All right, bye-bye.

12:42.010 --> 12:43.135
(EXHALES)

12:50.886 --> 12:53.128
How did you choose that tree?

12:55.655 --> 12:57.620
It was closest one to a pay phone.

13:04.556 --> 13:05.729
(DOOR CLOSES)

13:09.760 --> 13:10.917
Ohhh.

13:19.612 --> 13:20.769
Hey, Bec.

13:22.144 --> 13:23.808
I meant what I said before.

13:25.058 --> 13:26.394
You're gonna live forever.

13:26.753 --> 13:28.542
(SCOFFS) Okay, Jack.

13:30.081 --> 13:33.020
- That means I'm gonna go first.
- Jack...

13:33.120 --> 13:35.274
No, look, we don't
have to talk about it.

13:35.299 --> 13:36.599
- We don't.
- Just...

13:37.359 --> 13:38.956
don't put me in the ground.

13:40.343 --> 13:41.433
Okay?

13:44.784 --> 13:46.331
Let me be outside.

13:48.234 --> 13:49.464
Okay.

13:54.224 --> 13:56.823
Now can we just stop all that talk now?

13:59.118 --> 14:00.451
(SIGHS)

14:10.800 --> 14:12.393
Hi. We're here.

14:13.565 --> 14:14.776
Sir.

14:15.253 --> 14:16.463
Hi.

14:17.128 --> 14:18.766
Sorry. Um...

14:19.527 --> 14:21.160
I'm-I'm Rebecca Pearson.

14:21.162 --> 14:22.995
- I'm Jack's wife.
- Oh.

14:22.997 --> 14:25.364
- I'm sorry for your loss.
- Thank you.

14:25.979 --> 14:28.183
Uh, the service doesn't start
for another hour.

14:28.550 --> 14:30.703
No, I know, I know. I just wanted to...

14:31.298 --> 14:33.206
I wanted to be here when he arrived.

14:35.701 --> 14:37.433
Um, we'll go sit.

14:39.013 --> 14:40.183
(BIRDS CHIRPING)

15:08.167 --> 15:10.386
PASTOR: Jack Pearson was a good man.

15:11.495 --> 15:13.804
He was beloved by his community;

15:14.097 --> 15:17.776
by his children, Kate, Kevin, Randall;

15:18.636 --> 15:22.151
and his wife of 21 years, Rebecca.

15:23.127 --> 15:25.089
When I had to speak at my mom's funeral,

15:26.425 --> 15:28.925
I was really worried that
I, uh, might get choked up.

15:29.479 --> 15:32.456
And Jack told me
that if I were to get emotional,

15:32.458 --> 15:34.081
that I should just stop and...

15:34.854 --> 15:36.214
take a sip of water.

15:36.808 --> 15:39.253
But I'm not sure if there's
enough water in this world

15:40.886 --> 15:42.261
to get me through today.

15:43.151 --> 15:44.969
RANDALL: I hope that, uh, one day,

15:44.971 --> 15:48.151
I can find a love like
my father had for my mother

15:49.680 --> 15:51.081
and like she had for him.

15:57.220 --> 15:58.315
Mom.

15:58.855 --> 16:00.745
- Mom.
- Hmm?

16:01.069 --> 16:03.144
Everybody's leaving for the reception.

16:04.223 --> 16:06.245
- Are you ready to leave?
- Yeah.

16:07.745 --> 16:09.698
Excuse me. Sir.

16:10.440 --> 16:11.792
Uh, what happens now?

16:11.925 --> 16:14.745
Oh, I was just gonna transport
it for you to the reception.

16:14.770 --> 16:16.403
No, no, no, no. We'll take it.

16:16.607 --> 16:18.167
- Are you sure? We usually...
- Yes, I'm sure.

16:18.948 --> 16:20.198
- Thank you.
- Okay.

16:20.262 --> 16:21.573
Guys, let's go.

16:30.870 --> 16:33.596
Okay, Randall,
a good driver is flexible.

16:34.073 --> 16:35.697
- Got to be spontaneous.
- Okay.

16:36.041 --> 16:37.791
- Okay, foot on the brake.
- Mm-hmm.

16:37.901 --> 16:40.447
There you go. And turn the car
on. Don't overcrank it though.

16:40.472 --> 16:42.229
- (ENGINE STARTS)
- Go, go, go. There you go. Okay.

16:42.432 --> 16:44.564
Now, gear into drive.

16:44.589 --> 16:46.143
There you go. Foot off the brake.

16:46.168 --> 16:47.666
Put a little pressure on the gas.

16:50.128 --> 16:51.643
Off the brake. There you go.

16:51.668 --> 16:54.135
Give it a little bit more.
There you go. Eyes on the road.

16:57.721 --> 16:59.469
Dude, come on.

16:59.635 --> 17:01.729
RANDALL: It's my first time
on the road. Please.

17:02.211 --> 17:03.455
(ENGINE REVVING)

17:05.010 --> 17:06.165
Happy now?

17:06.214 --> 17:08.549
I mean, I'll probably be 40 by the
time we get around the block.

17:08.574 --> 17:10.006
And still living in Mom
and Dad's basement.

17:10.031 --> 17:11.940
- Hey, cool it, both of you.
- You know what, it's better than 40

17:11.964 --> 17:13.579
- and never being touched by a woman.
- Go to hell, Kev.

17:13.605 --> 17:15.532
- Hey, hey, watch! Look! Watch, watch!
- (TIRES SCREECH)

17:15.986 --> 17:17.635
Brake, brake, brake!

17:18.011 --> 17:19.854
Put it in park. Put it in park.

17:21.111 --> 17:22.877
- You guys okay?
- Yeah, I'm fine. -Yeah.

17:23.854 --> 17:25.987
- (JACK EXHALES)
- I'm s-sorry, I didn't...

17:26.042 --> 17:27.243
I didn't see it.

17:31.347 --> 17:32.463
Get out.

17:33.019 --> 17:34.237
You're walking home.

17:34.262 --> 17:36.229
- It's, like, five miles.
- Get out.

17:37.849 --> 17:39.190
(DOOR CLOSES)

17:43.256 --> 17:44.432
I'm sorry.

18:06.480 --> 18:08.002
Look, we're sorry, okay?

18:09.418 --> 18:10.783
It won't happen again.

18:12.983 --> 18:14.627
I don't understand you two.

18:16.681 --> 18:17.901
My brother and me...

18:19.115 --> 18:21.377
inseparable when we were your age.

18:24.704 --> 18:26.446
- What?
- RANDALL: Nothing.

18:26.582 --> 18:29.596
You just never talk about him
or anything when you were a kid.

18:30.260 --> 18:33.401
Yeah, well, what's there to talk
about? You know the big stuff.

18:34.314 --> 18:35.706
Our dad was a drunk.

18:36.049 --> 18:37.386
Our mom was depressed.

18:37.411 --> 18:40.815
Nicky... Nicky was my best friend.

18:41.121 --> 18:43.947
We went to war, and he died.

18:44.705 --> 18:47.072
Not exactly fun to reminisce.

19:01.947 --> 19:05.018
My brother and I, we had to
look out for each other.

19:06.916 --> 19:09.002
No one, no one was gonna do it for us.

19:09.225 --> 19:10.330
Okay?

19:10.871 --> 19:12.830
But you two, you're lucky.

19:13.546 --> 19:16.252
Nothing's forced you
to have each other's backs.

19:18.273 --> 19:20.306
So, you're either gonna

19:20.602 --> 19:24.104
decide to fix the stuff
that's broken between you

19:24.201 --> 19:25.268
or you're not.

19:25.911 --> 19:27.119
That's up to you.

19:27.646 --> 19:31.299
And I hope you do,
because, your mom and I,

19:32.379 --> 19:34.158
we're not gonna be around forever.

19:35.690 --> 19:38.604
And when we're gone,
the two of you and your sister

19:38.629 --> 19:41.197
are the only people on this planet

19:41.916 --> 19:44.244
who are gonna be able to look back

19:44.509 --> 19:47.182
and remember all the stuff
that's happened to you.

19:49.159 --> 19:51.487
I know that may not seem
like a big deal now,

19:51.611 --> 19:53.587
but trust me when I say it...

19:54.852 --> 19:55.869
it is.

20:00.806 --> 20:02.031
MAN: I really mean it.

20:02.056 --> 20:04.594
The office just isn't gonna be
the same without your dad there.

20:04.619 --> 20:07.219
RANDALL: Thank you so much.
My dad loved working with you.

20:07.749 --> 20:09.103
Appreciate it. Thank you.

20:13.853 --> 20:15.486
- Hey, hey.
- (RANDALL GRUNTS)

20:15.915 --> 20:16.915
What the hell, man?

20:16.940 --> 20:18.712
- Where'd you get Dad's watch?
- Mom brought it back

20:18.737 --> 20:20.423
- from the hospital.
- (SCOFFS) So you just decided

20:20.448 --> 20:21.931
- it's yours now?
- I asked her.

20:21.956 --> 20:23.978
- She said it was fine.
- Of course she did.

20:24.168 --> 20:25.298
Kevin.

20:26.152 --> 20:28.345
SHELLY: Why don't you just
come over tonight?

20:28.428 --> 20:30.695
Mom, did you say
Randall could have Dad's watch?

20:31.004 --> 20:32.642
- Kevin...
- You did.

20:33.072 --> 20:35.181
- Wow.
- What is the matter with you?

20:35.350 --> 20:37.116
You know what, man,
I'm tired of the act.

20:37.415 --> 20:39.477
I'm tired of watching you pretend to be

20:39.546 --> 20:41.158
- the new man of the house.
- I'm not trying to be the new...

20:41.183 --> 20:43.798
A real man would've stopped
Dad from going back in there.

20:47.387 --> 20:49.025
I would've never let Dad go back in.

20:49.050 --> 20:50.283
But you weren't there, Kev.

20:51.189 --> 20:53.345
- You're never there for anyone.
- KATE: Stop it.

20:53.767 --> 20:56.259
Seriously, what are you doing?
Look where we are.

20:58.865 --> 21:00.337
KATE: I'll go to the car.

21:04.149 --> 21:07.184
- I'm gonna go get some air.
- I'm sorry, Mom. I...

21:18.696 --> 21:20.602
<i>MAN (OVER RADIO):
Expect much more of the same</i>

21:20.618 --> 21:22.718
<i>over the next couple of days.
Might want to do something with</i>

21:22.720 --> 21:25.369
<i>those outdoor activities
that you've been saving up for.</i>

21:25.394 --> 21:27.294
<i>Well, it looks like
another wet one, folks.</i>

21:27.363 --> 21:29.663
<i>Get your umbrellas out
if you're going out.</i>

21:29.732 --> 21:31.899
<i>Possible thundershowers
over the next hours.</i>

21:31.967 --> 21:34.118
<i>Cloudy tomorrow with a 50% chance...</i>

21:35.337 --> 21:37.125
<i>It's gonna be a cold one, folks...</i>

21:39.446 --> 21:40.657
Excuse me, miss?

21:41.758 --> 21:43.544
Hey, Dad, I know this looks bad.

21:43.612 --> 21:45.946
It's 10:00 a.m. on a Thursday.
Doesn't look good.

21:46.015 --> 21:48.811
I know, but before
I tell you why I'm here,

21:48.836 --> 21:51.585
I think you should know that I
had no exams today, and that...

21:51.654 --> 21:52.907
Where you going, Kate?

21:53.703 --> 21:55.455
Alanis Morissette is signing copies

21:55.524 --> 21:57.532
of Jagged Little Pill
at Jerry's Records.

21:58.712 --> 22:00.212
Okay, Dad, come on.

22:00.280 --> 22:02.188
No one good ever comes to Pittsburgh.

22:02.213 --> 22:05.203
And now, by some gift of God,
Alanis Morissette,

22:05.228 --> 22:06.688
my favorite artist in the history

22:06.713 --> 22:07.789
of the world is coming...

22:07.814 --> 22:08.868
- Get in the car.
- Dad.

22:08.893 --> 22:10.711
Get in the car, Kate.

22:19.089 --> 22:20.625
Are you taking me back to school?

22:23.653 --> 22:25.618
No. I'm taking you to Jerry's Records.

22:30.914 --> 22:33.202
All right, so who's
this Atlantis character

22:33.227 --> 22:35.313
whose music trumps a good education?

22:35.849 --> 22:38.836
(MUTTERS) Dad, "Alanis," not "Atlantis."

22:38.861 --> 22:41.594
(CHUCKLES): Oh, like
that's a more normal name.

22:41.750 --> 22:43.282
- Mm.
- All right, let's hear it.

22:44.532 --> 22:46.196
- Okay.
- (CASSETTE CLICKS)

22:48.282 --> 22:49.969
- ♪ And it would knock me ♪
- (VOLUME INCREASES)

22:49.994 --> 22:53.125
♪ To the floor if I
wasn't there already ♪

22:53.313 --> 22:56.835
♪ If only I could hunt the hunter ♪

22:58.227 --> 23:00.243
- ♪ And all I really want... ♪
- I don't get it.

23:00.268 --> 23:02.535
- Yeah. See, I told you.
- Well, I mean,

23:02.560 --> 23:05.394
this-this is, this is like
complaining with a guitar, Kate.

23:05.419 --> 23:06.718
This isn't music.

23:06.743 --> 23:08.843
(LAUGHS) Well, Dad,
this won five Grammys.

23:08.868 --> 23:11.141
- No. Really?
- Yes. Yes.

23:11.772 --> 23:14.360
She's only, like,
six years older than me.

23:14.583 --> 23:16.024
- So crazy.
- No.

23:16.476 --> 23:17.481
(TURNS MUSIC OFF)

23:17.506 --> 23:18.633
That's taken years off of my life,

23:18.658 --> 23:19.633
- so, want to...
- All right.

23:19.658 --> 23:22.532
You want to hear...
you want to hear something?

23:22.622 --> 23:26.860
This... really...
gets underneath your skin.

23:26.885 --> 23:28.672
- ♪ Well, I sought gold ♪
- Huh?

23:29.680 --> 23:31.477
- Ah, Bruce.
- Yeah.

23:31.891 --> 23:33.593
You know, you are so predictable.

23:33.662 --> 23:35.061
- Predictable?
- Yeah.

23:35.399 --> 23:37.953
More like appreciating an American hero.

23:37.978 --> 23:39.618
Oh, all right. Calm down.

23:40.086 --> 23:41.461
(LAUGHS)

23:42.758 --> 23:43.860
You know, actually,

23:43.937 --> 23:46.321
your guy Bruce and Alanis
are not that different.

23:46.346 --> 23:47.633
Oh, yeah. How is that?

23:48.514 --> 23:51.071
I mean, musically,
they're nothing alike, but...

23:52.014 --> 23:54.774
but they do both use songs
to tell their stories,

23:54.799 --> 23:57.828
so, like, this intimacy comes through.

23:58.953 --> 24:00.921
They make you feel like
they're your best friend,

24:00.989 --> 24:04.000
but also you at the very same time.

24:05.407 --> 24:07.194
♪ From a house on a hill... ♪

24:07.262 --> 24:09.496
I'm sorry. Did my daughter get abducted

24:09.565 --> 24:12.365
by a veteran Rolling Stone critic?

24:12.434 --> 24:13.875
- Dad.
- (LAUGHS)

24:14.703 --> 24:19.109
♪ I walk through these rooms,
but none of them are mine... ♪

24:19.134 --> 24:20.711
I've been writing my own stuff.

24:21.196 --> 24:23.164
- ♪ Down empty hallways... ♪
- Yeah?

24:23.213 --> 24:26.883
Yeah. But honestly, it's just for fun.

24:26.908 --> 24:29.235
I mean, come on. I'm no Alanis.

24:30.469 --> 24:33.680
♪ Searching for my beautiful reward... ♪

24:33.748 --> 24:36.149
JACK: Okay, Jerry's Records,
here we are.

24:36.218 --> 24:38.368
- (GIGGLES)
- That'll be $18.50.

24:38.571 --> 24:40.203
- Yeah.
- Hey, Kate.

24:40.228 --> 24:41.313
Yeah.

24:43.071 --> 24:45.692
I think you ought to give music
some serious thought,

24:45.760 --> 24:47.297
you know, as a path.

24:48.500 --> 24:51.497
Dad, I read that 0.2 percent of people

24:51.566 --> 24:53.733
who start music careers
actually make it,

24:53.758 --> 24:55.902
so that's basically nobody.

24:55.971 --> 25:00.499
Okay, well, I read that 100%
of people that get caught up

25:00.524 --> 25:02.921
in "how many people make it" statistics

25:02.946 --> 25:05.704
- never actually make it.
- Really?

25:05.729 --> 25:06.961
- Yeah.
- You read that?

25:06.986 --> 25:08.797
- Sure did.
- Yeah.

25:09.610 --> 25:10.743
Hey, look.

25:12.196 --> 25:14.569
You may not be this Alanis...

25:15.008 --> 25:17.008
- Morissette.
- ...Morissette character,

25:17.039 --> 25:19.407
but you're Kate Pearson, okay?

25:20.508 --> 25:23.345
Whatever Kate Pearson
has her heart set on,

25:23.688 --> 25:24.985
she gets.

25:26.021 --> 25:28.508
Okay? Don't ever forget it.

25:32.532 --> 25:33.835
- Go. Go.
- Okay. (LAUGHS)

25:33.860 --> 25:35.180
- Have fun.
- (SQUEALS)

25:35.330 --> 25:37.397
- Thanks for the ride, Dad.
- Yeah, you got it.

25:40.336 --> 25:43.414
Hey, Bruce album, by the way...
pretty good, actually.

25:43.439 --> 25:46.633
Yeah? Hey, maybe I'll get us
tickets sometime!

25:47.941 --> 25:49.164
♪ ♪

26:22.961 --> 26:24.383
(WHISPERS): Hey, my Bug.

26:25.907 --> 26:27.118
(SNIFFLES)

26:29.381 --> 26:31.672
(SIGHS) How are you?

26:36.533 --> 26:38.493
I don't understand how he died.

26:43.674 --> 26:45.407
He went into cardiac arrest

26:45.432 --> 26:47.977
because he inhaled too much smoke.

26:54.602 --> 26:56.625
Because he went back inside, right?

26:57.485 --> 26:59.524
- I don't know.
- You know.

26:59.549 --> 27:01.882
- No, I don't know, Kate.
- You know.

27:02.407 --> 27:05.172
But the rest of us
didn't inhale too much smoke

27:05.197 --> 27:06.750
because we got out in time.

27:08.032 --> 27:11.532
But Dad... he... he would have
got out in time, too,

27:11.699 --> 27:14.453
but he went back inside, right?

27:18.086 --> 27:20.398
- (QUIETLY): I don't know.
- You do know.

27:21.640 --> 27:22.735
♪ ♪

27:36.367 --> 27:37.703
Hello, Rebecca.

27:57.047 --> 27:58.250
Hi.

28:01.195 --> 28:04.460
We have to stop meeting under
such dramatic circumstances.

28:04.485 --> 28:06.418
- (REBECCA CHUCKLES) Yes. Yes, we do.
- (LAUGHS)

28:07.304 --> 28:09.084
Uh, this is Anne. This is my wife.

28:09.109 --> 28:10.120
- Oh, hi.
- Hi.

28:10.145 --> 28:12.024
We just wanted to come pay our respects.

28:12.075 --> 28:14.281
I am so sorry for your loss.

28:15.344 --> 28:17.109
Nathan's told me all about your husband.

28:17.134 --> 28:19.984
How he used to come by
the hospital for advice

28:20.009 --> 28:21.859
every so often those first few years

28:21.884 --> 28:23.093
- when your kids were young.
- What?

28:23.118 --> 28:25.406
I kept trying to tell him,
"I don't know how to raise 'em,

28:25.431 --> 28:28.390
I just know how to deliver 'em,"
but he wouldn't stop coming.

28:28.669 --> 28:31.556
He'd gotten it into his head I was wise.

28:32.544 --> 28:34.007
I think it's your voice.

28:34.032 --> 28:36.109
- Oh. Oh.
- It's very soothing.

28:36.230 --> 28:39.226
- And your... lemon metaphors.
- (CHUCKLES)

28:39.265 --> 28:41.187
- The mustache helps, too.
- (LAUGHS)

28:41.225 --> 28:44.281
- Adds a certain gravitas.
- Mm, it does.

28:46.305 --> 28:47.460
ANNE: Well,

28:47.492 --> 28:49.515
- I'm gonna give you two a moment.
- Thank you, darlin'.

28:49.540 --> 28:51.601
It was so good to meet you, Rebecca.

28:51.626 --> 28:53.429
Nice to meet you. (SNIFFLES)

28:57.105 --> 28:58.312
I hate this thing.

28:59.477 --> 29:01.257
She's the one makes me use it.

29:02.477 --> 29:04.454
Says it's 'cause she loves me.

29:04.601 --> 29:05.978
- (SCOFFS)
- Hmm.

29:06.046 --> 29:07.847
I like her. (SNIFFLING)

29:07.992 --> 29:10.414
Yeah, yeah. Me, too.

29:10.885 --> 29:12.031
Me, too.

29:13.307 --> 29:14.414
Yup.

29:20.421 --> 29:22.281
So, what are you doing out here?

29:23.129 --> 29:24.437
(REBECCA SIGHS)

29:32.125 --> 29:34.226
(QUIETLY): I wasn't there when he died.

29:35.445 --> 29:36.506
I wasn't there.

29:36.531 --> 29:40.881
I... have been following
his urn around all day

29:40.906 --> 29:43.937
because I wasn't there,

29:44.328 --> 29:46.187
and I want to make up for it.

29:46.976 --> 29:48.101
Rebecca...

29:49.351 --> 29:50.914
I can't do this without him.

29:51.492 --> 29:52.764
(SNIFFLES) I just, I can't.

29:52.789 --> 29:54.589
He knew how to do all of this.

29:54.591 --> 29:56.591
He was... fearless.

29:56.655 --> 29:58.889
I'm not fearless. I'm not.

30:02.223 --> 30:03.483
(QUIETLY): Uh, yeah.

30:09.328 --> 30:10.976
Rebecca, um...

30:13.898 --> 30:15.443
I would never presume

30:15.468 --> 30:18.304
to know more about your
husband than you, hmm?

30:19.796 --> 30:21.375
But, um...

30:23.945 --> 30:26.029
the man I knew, the one

30:26.054 --> 30:30.815
that used to drop by my office
unannounced from time to time...

30:30.840 --> 30:33.835
now he had, uh, he had
a whole lot of fears.

30:36.171 --> 30:37.734
- He did?
- (LAUGHS): Oh.

30:38.593 --> 30:41.915
A new father is
the most fearful creature alive,

30:41.917 --> 30:44.140
and he was no exception. (CHUCKLES)

30:45.170 --> 30:46.251
No.

30:49.104 --> 30:52.573
Fears about his wife
and about his children.

30:58.156 --> 31:04.273
About being able to keep them
happy and healthy... safe.

31:08.203 --> 31:11.406
But he did a pretty good job taking
care of his family, now, didn't he?

31:11.868 --> 31:13.640
- Yeah.
- Yeah.

31:15.454 --> 31:17.258
- And so will you.
- Oh.

31:18.356 --> 31:21.127
I can't, not without him.

31:21.152 --> 31:23.492
- Now, hold on. Hold on, now.
- (SIGHS)

31:23.517 --> 31:25.507
You are the same woman...

31:26.905 --> 31:28.531
who lost a child

31:28.901 --> 31:32.803
and rolled out of my hospital
with three babies just the same.

31:33.142 --> 31:35.813
You're as tough as they come,
Rebecca Pearson.

31:38.892 --> 31:40.523
- Not without him.
- Bullcrap.

31:40.548 --> 31:42.750
- Not without him!
- Bullcrap.

31:46.079 --> 31:47.376
- Rebecca?
- (SNIFFLES)

31:50.124 --> 31:51.407
- Rebecca.
- I know.

31:51.994 --> 31:53.859
I know. I know. (SNIFFLES)

31:54.275 --> 31:56.585
Take the sourest lemons

31:56.610 --> 31:59.195
and make something
resembling lemonade, right?

32:00.377 --> 32:03.892
You didn't just make something
resembling lemonade, dear.

32:07.940 --> 32:11.100
You made one of the sweetest
damn pitchers of lemonade

32:11.102 --> 32:12.570
- I ever saw.
- (SOBS)

32:17.297 --> 32:19.250
So don't you try and sell me

32:19.275 --> 32:21.275
- on what you can't do,
- (SNIFFLES)

32:21.300 --> 32:23.300
because I'm too old, I'm too smart,

32:23.325 --> 32:24.703
and I'm not buying it.

32:32.479 --> 32:35.820
Now, I would like
to punctuate my inspiring speech

32:35.845 --> 32:38.796
by standing up, winking at you,
and then walking away.

32:41.257 --> 32:44.000
But I'm old, and all that
would take at least six minutes.

32:44.025 --> 32:45.291
(LAUGHS)

32:47.498 --> 32:48.703
(SIGHING)

32:57.494 --> 33:00.181
Can I just sit here with
you for a little bit?

33:04.960 --> 33:06.234
(GROANS SOFTLY)

33:07.968 --> 33:09.451
(SNIFFLES, SIGHS)

33:09.476 --> 33:11.899
DR. K: Sitting is what
I'm best at these days.

33:24.116 --> 33:25.639
Do you think we bought enough food?

33:25.664 --> 33:28.402
Hey, it's the Super Bowl, Kev. You
know we don't skimp on that.

33:28.427 --> 33:29.452
(KEVIN CHUCKLES)

33:29.624 --> 33:31.592
Hey, dude, your cast
is really digging in my leg.

33:31.617 --> 33:33.374
At least your leg's fully functional.

33:33.399 --> 33:35.827
KATE: Kev, quit whining.
Your cast comes off in two days.

33:35.895 --> 33:38.577
Oh, hey, nobody make any plans
for next Saturday.

33:38.655 --> 33:39.944
- All right?
- Why?

33:39.969 --> 33:42.567
- Because I have a surprise for us.
- Really?

33:42.635 --> 33:44.866
- All of you.
- (CHUCKLING)

33:45.178 --> 33:46.749
- Don't worry about it.
- Okay.

33:47.366 --> 33:48.652
REBECCA: Hmm.

33:48.677 --> 33:49.944
(JACK SIGHS)

33:54.444 --> 33:56.108
JACK: Okay, everyone get a bag.

33:56.626 --> 33:57.959
REBECCA: I'll get your crutches.

33:58.028 --> 34:00.210
- KEVIN: Thanks.
- JACK: Kev, you are off duty

34:00.235 --> 34:03.108
because of your injury.

34:05.753 --> 34:07.460
Need a hand? Or a foot?

34:07.485 --> 34:08.748
Give me those.

34:10.795 --> 34:12.545
There you go. You got the bag?

34:13.143 --> 34:14.991
Let's make some dinner, okay?

34:15.485 --> 34:16.670
♪ ♪

34:29.110 --> 34:30.172
Hey.

34:30.268 --> 34:32.156
- Are you ready to go? Okay.
- Yeah.

34:32.293 --> 34:34.283
Hey, Randall, we're leaving.

34:34.308 --> 34:35.687
- Already?
- Yeah.

34:35.712 --> 34:37.206
- Shouldn't we say bye?
- Now.

34:37.315 --> 34:38.934
Hey, where is your sister?

34:38.958 --> 34:40.667
- I think she's outside.
- Okay.

34:40.692 --> 34:41.831
Then let's go.

34:45.683 --> 34:46.853
♪ ♪

35:07.618 --> 35:09.369
All right. Let's go.

35:11.078 --> 35:12.376
(ENGINE STARTS)

35:16.981 --> 35:18.197
♪ ♪

35:39.596 --> 35:41.236
Do you guys remember the story

35:41.261 --> 35:43.744
about the first time
your father brought me out here?

35:44.659 --> 35:47.360
Yeah. When you had your cancer scare.

35:47.875 --> 35:49.548
He said it was his favorite tree.

35:49.845 --> 35:51.512
Even though he'd never been.

35:51.537 --> 35:52.587
Okay.

35:53.339 --> 35:55.908
Guess we had told you
that one before, huh?

36:01.103 --> 36:03.885
Did you know that when your
father and I first got married,

36:03.953 --> 36:06.626
I wasn't sure that I ever
wanted to have kids?

36:07.884 --> 36:08.947
I mean...

36:10.138 --> 36:12.470
I figured I would eventually, but...

36:17.728 --> 36:18.869
(CHUCKLES SOFTLY)

36:19.728 --> 36:21.869
He was the worst at movies.

36:22.876 --> 36:24.105
Wasn't he?

36:24.353 --> 36:25.978
He was just the worst.

36:26.181 --> 36:28.176
I mean, as soon as the movie started,

36:28.244 --> 36:29.665
he would just...

36:31.189 --> 36:34.595
figure out who would end up
with who or who murdered who.

36:35.369 --> 36:39.244
Somehow he was always, always right.

36:40.189 --> 36:43.165
It's like he could see things
before they happened.

36:44.915 --> 36:46.158
You know?

36:47.837 --> 36:49.517
I mean, he could see you three...

36:50.346 --> 36:51.642
before you happened.

36:54.807 --> 36:56.064
Thank God he did.

37:00.154 --> 37:01.408
♪ ♪

37:08.173 --> 37:09.345
Hey.

37:11.107 --> 37:12.392
You know neither of you

37:12.417 --> 37:14.603
has to be the man
of the house now, right?

37:14.978 --> 37:17.786
You're two 17-year-olds, okay?

37:17.855 --> 37:22.072
Your only job from now on,
your only job is to...

37:23.295 --> 37:24.670
go on dates

37:25.037 --> 37:27.798
and hang out with your friends
and your sister, and...

37:28.525 --> 37:30.933
I wouldn't protest if you wanted
to do a load of laundry

37:31.002 --> 37:32.267
every now and then.

37:33.322 --> 37:36.212
But that's it. Okay?

37:36.255 --> 37:37.788
Mm-hmm. Okay.

37:40.736 --> 37:43.299
And, Kate, sweetheart,

37:44.337 --> 37:45.814
I know no matter what I say,

37:45.883 --> 37:47.718
no matter what anybody else says,

37:47.743 --> 37:49.915
you're gonna blame yourself

37:50.708 --> 37:52.680
for your father going back
in the house to get Louie.

37:52.705 --> 37:54.251
- Mom, please don't.
- No, no, no, no.

37:54.276 --> 37:55.431
Listen to me.

37:56.558 --> 38:00.298
Because it was not your fault.

38:00.327 --> 38:01.467
Do you hear me?

38:01.492 --> 38:05.127
He was a grown man, Kate,
who made a choice.

38:06.632 --> 38:08.517
And if I have to spend
the rest of my life

38:08.542 --> 38:10.564
making sure that you know that, I will.

38:11.380 --> 38:12.406
Okay?

38:18.689 --> 38:19.884
(SNIFFLES) Okay.

38:22.100 --> 38:23.891
- Are you ready?
- (QUIET SOBBING)

38:24.810 --> 38:26.827
Yeah? Yeah.

38:31.204 --> 38:32.403
It's okay.

38:33.599 --> 38:34.790
♪ ♪

38:49.630 --> 38:50.845
(SOBS SOFTLY)

39:02.807 --> 39:04.330
- Mom?
- What?

39:04.355 --> 39:07.603
Mom, is it possible
that we don't do all of it?

39:08.146 --> 39:09.431
Yes. Yeah, yeah, yeah.

39:09.456 --> 39:11.290
- Sure, that's fine.
- Okay.

39:15.753 --> 39:17.103
You guys... (SNIFFLES)

39:19.307 --> 39:23.056
he got us tickets to go see
Bruce Springsteen tonight

39:23.081 --> 39:24.407
at the Benedum Center.

39:25.644 --> 39:27.093
I think we should go.

39:29.372 --> 39:31.305
What do you think? Should we go?

39:32.679 --> 39:33.764
Yeah.

39:34.393 --> 39:35.639
Yeah, we should go.

39:36.174 --> 39:38.441
- We should go.
- I think so, too.

39:40.931 --> 39:43.040
All right, can you give me
just one moment here,

39:43.065 --> 39:44.447
and I'll meet you guys back at the car?

39:44.472 --> 39:46.199
- Yeah.
- Okay.

39:46.940 --> 39:48.062
♪ ♪

40:11.281 --> 40:13.097
We're gonna be okay, baby.

40:15.318 --> 40:17.664
I promise you, we're gonna be okay.

40:24.881 --> 40:26.303
JACK: Here's the thing, Mel.

40:26.576 --> 40:29.008
I don't want to buy one of
those used cars out there.

40:29.787 --> 40:31.340
- No?
- That Wagoneer...

40:31.365 --> 40:32.801
that's my family's car.

40:34.814 --> 40:36.962
I, you know... I can see it so clearly.

40:37.305 --> 40:38.415
It's...

40:39.498 --> 40:41.830
sturdy, tough.

40:42.976 --> 40:44.759
Pearsons, we need tough.

40:45.069 --> 40:46.711
Because I can tell you right now,

40:46.780 --> 40:48.203
there's gonna be scrapes.

40:48.228 --> 40:49.931
I did something bad parking.

40:49.956 --> 40:51.036
And dings.

40:51.061 --> 40:52.416
- (BALL THUMPS)
- Oops.

40:52.678 --> 40:53.806
Stains.

40:53.831 --> 40:55.220
- (RANDALL GASPS)
- It's okay.

40:55.245 --> 40:56.447
- Oh, my God.
- Randall!

40:56.472 --> 40:58.158
So many stains.

40:58.580 --> 41:00.064
But that's okay.

41:00.168 --> 41:04.224
Because every battle scar
is gonna be another memory.

41:06.366 --> 41:07.486
♪ ♪

41:11.393 --> 41:13.570
But eventually, that car out there,

41:13.595 --> 41:16.235
that car is gonna tell my family's story

41:16.260 --> 41:18.649
just by looking at it.

41:19.016 --> 41:20.484
But here's the thing, Mel.

41:22.352 --> 41:23.736
I can't afford that car.

41:24.270 --> 41:25.361
I can't.

41:25.899 --> 41:27.806
Which is why I need you to help me.

41:28.484 --> 41:30.062
I mean, as parents...

41:31.773 --> 41:36.369
we talk a lot about what we want
for our kids, right?

41:37.050 --> 41:38.929
I mean, I know I think about it a lot.

41:39.127 --> 41:40.555
What I want for mine.

41:41.336 --> 41:46.158
And I can come up with a fancy word

41:46.183 --> 41:48.111
that's gonna make me sound

41:48.136 --> 41:50.759
a whole lot smarter
than I actually am, but...

41:51.792 --> 41:55.728
the one word I keep coming back to is...

41:56.304 --> 41:57.492
"okay."

41:59.338 --> 42:01.290
I want my kids to be okay, Mel.

42:02.273 --> 42:03.814
I want my family to be okay.

42:07.323 --> 42:08.504
So, will you help me?

42:08.550 --> 42:10.500
Will you help me take care of my family?

42:10.756 --> 42:14.853
Because I see it, Mel.
I see it so clearly.

42:15.691 --> 42:17.190
♪ ♪

42:27.102 --> 42:31.236
I see my family okay in that car.

